1. Start a new document, problemset3.Rmd, in your soc10problemsets repository. (You can download a template [here](https://github.com/Soc10Spring2026/soc10problemsets_templates), but be sure to save it in your own soc10problemsets repo). Change your name in the header. Load the `gapminder` data using `library(gapminder)`. Create a simple plot with two of the variables. __Commit__ your changes. 

Here I created a plot that illustrates life expectancy across continents. Meaning, the x axis is the regions and y axis is the average life expectancy for each continent. Each dot depicts a continent during a specific year. 

```{r q1, echo = TRUE}

library(gapminder)
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(data = gapminder, 
            mapping = aes(x = continent, y = lifeExp))+
  geom_point()

```

2. Now, modify your plot! For each change that you make, explain your decision, in terms of the visual elements. __Commit__ your changes. 

Now for question 2 looking at question one made it hard to understand what the data was showing me, so to make it more clear I made a few changes. First, I created a boxplot to show the median and range of life expectancy. I then made the box plot black so it would be easy to compare with each continent clearly where the range of life expectancy was. I also added jittered points which means that it spreads the points out to prevent them from being as cluttered and overlapping as they were in question 1. Next, I added color to make it easy to differentiate each continent from one another. After doing this, I then assigned each continent a color to make it easy to draw comparisons. Lastly, I improved the labels and gave it a title, x and y axis to help the reader to know how to interpret this data visual. 

```{r q2, echo = TRUE}

ggplot(gapminder, 
      mapping = aes(x = continent, y = lifeExp, col = continent))+
geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.5)+
geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3, width = 0.3)+
scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "pink", "orange", "green", "blue))+
labs(title = "Life Expectancy by Continent",
x = "Continent",
y = "Life Expectancy",
col = "Continent")

```

3. Use the code provided to load data on racial compositions in California. Then create your own visualization! Try to make it different than what is done above. Is there anything that you want to change, but are unable to? Describe what you want to communicate with these data. __Commit__ your changes. 

I used the data to show how California's racial composition has changed from 2000-2020. I used what we learned in class to use bar chart to show the various percentages of each ethnic group. By keeping them separated from each time group 2000, 2010, 2020 it allows you to see the difference between each demographic over a large period of time. Before I started, I used head() and names() to understand the data set and organize how I want to convey this information. I made the data into the long format because I thought it would be better to more cleanly showing the data in one column "Year" and the percents into the column "Percent" instead of all in separate one's. Finally, I used facet wrap to separate the visual into three panels to clearly show the change over time, and to make for quick compairson.

```{r q3, echo = TRUE, message = FALSE}

library(readr)
library(RCurl)

# input url from github
url <- getURL("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tylermcdaniel/soc10/refs/heads/deployment/Data/ca_dem_table.csv")

# download wikipedia data (from github)
ca_dem_table <- read_csv(url)

head(ca_dem_table)
names(ca_dem_table)

library(tidyr)
library(magrittr)
library(dplyr)

ca_dem_table %<>%
            pivot_longer(cols = c("2000_pct", "2010_pct", "2020_pct"),
            names_to = "Year",
            values_to = "Percent")
ggplot(ca_dem_table,
            aes(x= Race, y = Percent, fill = Race))+
geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
labs(title = "Racial Composition in California",
            x = "",
            y = "Percent") +
theme_linedraw()+
theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
            axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
            legend.position = "none") +
facet_wrap(~Year)

```

4. Return to a dataset you have worked with in this class already (for example, hand-collected data, data using the `data()` function. The `gtrendsR` data could also work but may need some cleaning/manipulation). Use `ggplot()` to plot this data in a new way. Describe whether the viewer learns anything new from seeing the data in this way. __Commit__ your changes.  

I used the data set gapminder to find a different way to visualize the changes in average life expectancy over time across each continent. In comparison to the box plot I did in question 1 I think this line plot actually allows you to more quickly understand which continent has the highest average of life and grasp the comparison more efficient. When looking broadly at this graph it is easy to see that each continent has improve slightly in life expectancy, with some more than others but all showing improvement. Overall, I think this graph allowed to see long term trend more clearly to compare to other continents. 

```{r q4, echo = TRUE}

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(gapminder)

gapminder %<>%
            group_by(continent, year( %<>%
            summarize(avg_lifeExp = mean(lifeExp)) %<>%
            ggplot(aes(x = year, y = avg_lifeExp, color = continent)) +
            geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
            geom_point() +
            labs(title = "Average Life Expectancy Over Time By Continent",
            x = "Year",
            y = "Average Life Expectancy") +
            theme_minimal()

```


